{"_path":"/posts/drupal-views-3-contextual-filter","_dir":"posts","_draft":false,"_partial":false,"_locale":"","title":"Drupal - Views 3 Contextual Filter LIKE","description":"How to modify a Drupal/Views 3 Contextual Filter to use the LIKE operator, instead of the hard-coded =.","imagesource":null,"imagecredit":null,"image":"2012.08.21T140000_drupal-views-3-contextual-filter.png","createdAt":"2012-08-21T14:00:00","updatedAt":"2012-08-21T14:00:00","readingTime":{"text":"1 min read","minutes":0.685,"time":41100,"words":137},"body":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Hi folks,"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"While working with Drupal 7/Views 3 recently, I found a necessity to use the MySQL \"LIKE\" operator in place of the hard-coded \"=\" in a contextual filter. On researching this, I couldn't find anywhere in Views where this could be set up. To me, it seems insane that this isn't in there already, so if there's any way of doing this in Views UI, please do let me know!"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Anyway... What I needed was a contextual filter on the view which would find any node of a certain type which contained a particular string. If the string was static, I could have easily applied it as a filter criterion, however I needed to extract it from the URL. Not finding any simple way of applying a dynamic piece of text to a filter criterion, I decided that the most sensible option would be to try and modify the query. Fortunately, Views 3 provides this as a hook. The "},{"type":"element","tag":"a","props":{"href":"http://api.drupal.org/api/drupal","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Drupal API documentation"}]},{"type":"text","value":" provides a "},{"type":"element","tag":"a","props":{"href":"http://api.drupal.org/api/views/views.api.php/7","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"list of all the Views hooks which are provided for your use"}]},{"type":"text","value":"."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In Drupal, to implement a hook, you need to write a custom module. I'll go through the whole process here, so no worries if you're not familiar with the process."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"First, create a folder called \"customviewsquery\" under your Drupal installation, in the folder \"sites/all/modules\". Next, create the following file in the newly created folder."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"pre","props":{"className":"language-ini shiki shiki-themes github-dark","code":"name = Custom Views Query\ndescription = Modifies a single Views 3 contextual filter to use LIKE instead of =\ncore = 7.x\n\npackage = Custom Code\n","language":"ini","meta":"","style":""},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"code","props":{"__ignoreMap":""},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"class":"line","line":1},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"style":"--shiki-default:#F97583"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"name"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"style":"--shiki-default:#E1E4E8"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":" = Custom Views Query\n"}]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"class":"line","line":2},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"style":"--shiki-default:#F97583"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"description"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"style":"--shiki-default:#E1E4E8"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":" = Modifies a single Views 3 contextual filter to use LIKE instead "}]},{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"style":"--shiki-default:#F97583"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"of"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"style":"--shiki-default:#E1E4E8"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":" =\n"}]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"span","props":{"class":"line"